  "problemSolved": {
    "statement": "Intellectual property is generally characterized as non-physical property that is the product of original thought. Typically, rights do not surround the abstract non-physical entity; rather, intellectual property rights surround the control of physical manifestations or expressions of ideas. Intellectual property law protects a content-creator's interest in their ideas by assigning and enforcing legal rights to produce and control physical instantiations of those ideas. Legal protections for intellectual property have a rich history that stretches back to ancient Greece and before. As different legal systems matured in protecting intellectual works, there was a refinement of what was being protected within different areas. Over the same period several strands of moral justification for intellectual property were offered: namely, personality-based, utilitarian, and Lockean. Finally, there have been numerous critics of intellectual property and systems of intellectual property protection. This essay will discuss all of these topics, focusing on Anglo-American and European legal and moral conceptions of intellectual property.",
    "context": "Opening section: 1. History of Intellectual Property | Related entries: consequentialism, desert, freedom-speech, hegel, locke, marx, property, rights",
    "cynefinDomain": "complicated"
  },
